snippet.textDisplay: I completely agree with this assessment although I have to say that, for the most part I was not entertained. The lack of character development and even the backpeddaling on some character development left me with little interest or attachment to any character or what was going on with the exception of what was happening to Ben and Rey, and this was only due to the excellent performances by the 2 leads despite excruciatingly clunky dialogue they had to work with. It's a testament to their skill that they both shone, despite JJs best efforts. The worst aspect was most certainly reversal or skimming over of almost every aspect of TLJ and even,what appeared to be, pointed attempts to take shots at its predecessor, particularly during the moment with force ghost Luke and the talk of the Holdo manoeuvre. It felt bad spirited and left me feeling uncomfortable. JJ's checklist of fan service items left me yawning. Writing out Rose's part also felt completely disingenuous particularly as the film gained numerous superfluous characters who add little to the plot. Were it not for Adam and Daisy, I would have come away bitterly disappointed. This films fails both of their characters spectacularly for different reasons, both of which will haunt me in my sleep. I did think it looked nice though and John Williams always delivers.

snippet.textDisplay:
I don't really know how I feel about this movie. I've only seen it once, I guess that i have to process it for a little while. That being said my initial feeling upon leaving the cinema is that it is better then TLJ but the film/trilogy has ultimately has been limited by TLJ.

TLJ left the TROS with very little room to maneuver with only one film left. Rian Johnson set up very little, and wasted far more story arcs then he gave. I understand totally what he was trying to do and on some level I like that he was brave enough to try it, but for me and many others his shortcomings as a writer in this setting overshadowed his excellent visual style. Disney choosing a director who focuses heavily on themes seems to have been a missed step. I cant help but wonder if he was given the first film it might have turned out a bit better (I doubt it) subverting expectations is not a plot device that everyone is going to appreciate especially among normal hardcore SW fans (not the weird ones that abuse everybody) and definitely not in the middle act of a trilogy. In the end JJ was given lemons and made a lemonade that may have not been to everyone's taste.
I think my final thoughts on these movies as a whole are that although I dont think the Disney sequels are not the worst movies individually, they definitely seem like the most disjointed trilogy

Just to add a little bit to what Mark said about Johnsons views on the situation on the storm around the TLJ. Some of the things that were said to Johnson and other people were terrible, but what Johnson seems to have forgotten and maybe not everyone is aware of, is that during that whole time some of Johnson tweets were not particularly kind to say the least. Rian Johnson behaved appallingly to some fans on Twitter who were asking seemingly fairly honest questions, he is not totally innocent. He put out a fair few spicy tweets after TLJ (and seemingly long before TLJ judging by the sheer volume of tweets he deleted). As much as he wanted to claim that he was positive about the whole thing, his actions certainly feed into the negativity surrounding his movie.

snippet.textDisplay:
Forty-two years ago, I began a journey through the galaxy in a cinema in Tankerton.
It took me to places I could never have conceived, gave me dreams which showed me glimpses of the future, and filled me with aspirations to be more than I am.

At times, the journey took some unexpected, unwanted, undesirable directions, from which our collective memories recoil, and which filled me with a deep fear for how my journey would conclude.

That adventure has now ended, with a tumultuous onslaught of relentless emotions, tied together with a familiar score, penned by the masterful hand of John Williams.

Despite all I had read and seen telling me that what I just experienced would be the death-knell of the hopes and dreams of my childhood, I was carried aloft with each new scene.

There wasn't time to catch my breath as one frame fed into the next, highs and lows shocking me into anger and then slapped awake by sleight of hand and the realisation of my folly.

My fears were unfounded, the epic of my youth rekindled and far brighter than the previous abomination led me to expect.
My journey began a long time ago, in a galaxy far, far away, and it has ended strong and bright in memories I can hold dear once more.

Maybe there can be hope for the future.

snippet.textDisplay:
I've really lost faith in Mark's ability to evaluate stories in the last couple of years, specifically in the context of 'what's the moral of the story?'. The reason JJ Abrams ran away from the pure cynicism that was 'The Last Jedi' is precisely because there's nowhere to go with it: the cinematic equivalent of turning down a dead-end road. JJ had the unenviable job of concluding the story of this trilogy which was always going to prove difficult since no story actually emerged in the first two instalments and JJ's never been a talented writer to begin with.

Have you noticed how no-one, including Mike and Jay of RLM fame can actually flesh out a story involving a "grey side of the force"? That's because deep down they know that for all the cynical plot lines you could come up with you can't write a cynical story and expect people to like it's inevitably dissatisfying (non)conclusion, especially when you're talking about 'Star Wars'.

Look to 'Game of Thrones' as a prime example of how you can't satisfyingly conclude a story revolving around cynicism and moral ambiguity.
